<Content>A serene feeling for traditional Japan We stayed in the Main Building for 3 nights (4 days) in mid-April. My husband's business connection made the reservation at a corporate rate. The room was ample, with a good bath and amenities. The queen size bed was firm but comfortable. The hotel is huge, but as others noted, well-marked with signage and there are always staff to help. Breakfasts in the Terrace and Camellia are excellent. The sushi is fantastic. The teppan-yaki restaurant is also very fine. They have incredible wine lists and assortments of champagnes that are hard to find in most US cities. Nothing is moderately priced, but that's to be expected...it's a top Tokyo hotel. One annoying thing is that if you want to pay for a bar bill in cash (as opposed to sign for it) they routinely have not added the taxes, so a waiter will come running after you to get you to pay more (after you thought you'd paid and left a nice tip...). I finally gave up and just signed the bills...and got rid of my excess yen at checkout. The decor and ambiance are very 1960-1970 modern. One keeps expecting Sean Connery to come across the lobby on his way to meet Tiger Tanaka... Be sure to visit the museum across the driveway. There are free tickets in your room...it's a very nice art collection. 
